# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: vpn-tunneling
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:vpn-tunneling/generic-routing-encapsulation] Based on the principles of protocol layering in OSI, protocol encapsulation, not specifically GRE, breaks the layering order.
[src:vpn-tunneling/generic-routing-encapsulation] It may be viewed as a separator between two different protocol stacks, one acting as a carrier for another.
[src:vpn-tunneling/generic-routing-encapsulation] GRE packets that are encapsulated within IP directly, use IP protocol type 47 in the IPv4 header's *Protocol* field or the IPv6 header's *Next Header* field.
[src:vpn-tunneling/generic-routing-encapsulation] For performance reasons, GRE can also be encapsulated in UDP packets.
[src:vpn-tunneling/generic-routing-encapsulation] Better throughput may be achieved by using Equal-cost multi-path routing.
[src:vpn-tunneling/generic-routing-encapsulation] Set to 1 if a sequence number is present.
[src:vpn-tunneling/generic-routing-encapsulation] bit is set; contains the checksum for the GRE header and payload.
[src:vpn-tunneling/generic-routing-encapsulation] bit is set; contains an application-specific key value.
[src:vpn-tunneling/generic-routing-encapsulation] bit is set; contains a sequence number for the GRE packet.
[src:vpn-tunneling/generic-routing-encapsulation] A standard GRE packet header structure is represented in the diagram below.
[src:vpn-tunneling/generic-routing-encapsulation] Set to 1 if Routing and Offset information are present.
[src:vpn-tunneling/generic-routing-encapsulation] bit is set; contains a list of source route entries, therefore is of variable length.
[src:vpn-tunneling/generic-routing-encapsulation] The Point-to-Point Tunneling Protocol (PPTP) uses a variant GRE packet header structure, represented below.
[src:vpn-tunneling/generic-routing-encapsulation] PPTP creates a GRE tunnel through which the PPTP GRE packets are sent.
[src:vpn-tunneling/generic-routing-encapsulation] Set to 1 if a sequence number is supplied, indicating a PPTP GRE data packet.
[src:vpn-tunneling/generic-routing-encapsulation] For PPTP GRE packets, these are set to 0.
[src:vpn-tunneling/generic-routing-encapsulation] Set to 1 if an acknowledgment number is supplied, indicating a PPTP GRE acknowledgment packet.
[src:vpn-tunneling/generic-routing-encapsulation] For PPTP GRE packets, this is set to hex 880B.
[src:vpn-tunneling/generic-routing-encapsulation] Contains the size of the payload, not including the GRE header.
[src:vpn-tunneling/generic-routing-encapsulation] Contains the Peer's Call ID for the session to which the packet belongs.
[src:vpn-tunneling/generic-routing-encapsulation] Present if the S bit is set; contains the GRE payload sequence number.
[src:vpn-tunneling/generic-routing-encapsulation] Present if the A bit is set; contains the sequence number of the highest GRE payload packet received by the sender.
[src:vpn-tunneling/layer-2-tunneling-protocol] In computer networking, **Layer 2 Tunneling Protocol** (**L2TP**) is a tunneling protocol used to support virtual private networks (VPNs) or as part of the delivery of services by ISPs.
[src:vpn-tunneling/layer-2-tunneling-protocol] It uses encryption ('hiding') only for its own control messages (using an optional pre-shared secret), and does not provide any encryption or confidentiality of content by itself.
[src:vpn-tunneling/layer-2-tunneling-protocol] Rather, it provides a tunnel for Layer 2 (which may be encrypted), and the tunnel itself may be passed over a Layer 3 encryption protocol such as IPsec.
[src:vpn-tunneling/layer-2-tunneling-protocol] Published in August 1999 as proposed standard RFC 2661, L2TP has its origins primarily in two older tunneling protocols for point-to-point communication: Cisco's Layer 2 Forwarding Protocol (L2F) and Microsoft's Point-to-Point Tunneling Protocol (PPTP).
[src:vpn-tunneling/layer-2-tunneling-protocol] A new version of this protocol, L2TPv3, appeared as proposed standard RFC 3931 in 2005.
[src:vpn-tunneling/layer-2-tunneling-protocol] L2TPv3 provides additional security features, improved encapsulation, and the ability to carry data links other than simply Point-to-Point Protocol (PPP) over an IP network (for example: Frame Relay, Ethernet, ATM, etc.).
[src:vpn-tunneling/layer-2-tunneling-protocol] The entire L2TP packet, including payload and L2TP header, is sent within a User Datagram Protocol (UDP) datagram.
[src:vpn-tunneling/layer-2-tunneling-protocol] A virtue of transmission over UDP (rather than TCP) is that it avoids the TCP meltdown problem.
[src:vpn-tunneling/layer-2-tunneling-protocol] It is common to carry PPP sessions within an L2TP tunnel.
[src:vpn-tunneling/layer-2-tunneling-protocol] L2TP does not provide confidentiality or strong authentication by itself.
[src:vpn-tunneling/layer-2-tunneling-protocol] IPsec is often used to secure L2TP packets by providing confidentiality, authentication and integrity.
[src:vpn-tunneling/layer-2-tunneling-protocol] The combination of these two protocols is generally known as L2TP/IPsec (discussed below).
[src:vpn-tunneling/layer-2-tunneling-protocol] The two endpoints of an L2TP tunnel are called the L2TP access concentrator (LAC) and the L2TP network server (LNS).
[src:vpn-tunneling/layer-2-tunneling-protocol] Once a tunnel is established, the network traffic between the peers is bidirectional.
[src:vpn-tunneling/layer-2-tunneling-protocol] To be useful for networking, higher-level protocols are then run through the L2TP tunnel.
[src:vpn-tunneling/layer-2-tunneling-protocol] To facilitate this, an L2TP *session* is established within the tunnel for each higher-level protocol such as PPP.
[src:vpn-tunneling/layer-2-tunneling-protocol] Either the LAC or LNS may initiate sessions.
[src:vpn-tunneling/layer-2-tunneling-protocol] The traffic for each session is isolated by L2TP, so it is possible to set up multiple virtual networks across a single tunnel.
[src:vpn-tunneling/layer-2-tunneling-protocol] The packets exchanged within an L2TP tunnel are categorized as either *control packets* or *data packets*.
[src:vpn-tunneling/layer-2-tunneling-protocol] L2TP provides reliability features for the control packets, but no reliability for data packets.
[src:vpn-tunneling/layer-2-tunneling-protocol] Reliability, if desired, must be provided by the nested protocols running within each session of the L2TP tunnel.
[src:vpn-tunneling/layer-2-tunneling-protocol] L2TP allows the creation of a virtual private dialup network (VPDN) to connect a remote client to its corporate network by using a shared infrastructure, which could be the Internet or a service provider's network.
[src:vpn-tunneling/layer-2-tunneling-protocol] An L2TP tunnel can extend across an entire PPP session or only across one segment of a two-segment session.
[src:vpn-tunneling/layer-2-tunneling-protocol] control flags indicating data/control packet and presence of length, sequence, and offset fields.
[src:vpn-tunneling/layer-2-tunneling-protocol] Total length of the message in bytes, present only when length flag is set.
[src:vpn-tunneling/layer-2-tunneling-protocol] Indicates the identifier for the control connection.
[src:vpn-tunneling/layer-2-tunneling-protocol] Indicates the identifier for a session within a tunnel.
[src:vpn-tunneling/layer-2-tunneling-protocol] sequence number for expected message to be received.
[src:vpn-tunneling/layer-2-tunneling-protocol] In data messages, Nr is reserved and, if present (as indicated by the S bit), MUST be ignored upon receipt..
[src:vpn-tunneling/layer-2-tunneling-protocol] Specifies where payload data is located past the L2TP header.
[src:vpn-tunneling/layer-2-tunneling-protocol] If the offset field is present, the L2TP header ends after the last byte of the offset padding.
[src:vpn-tunneling/layer-2-tunneling-protocol] This field exists if the offset flag is set.
[src:vpn-tunneling/layer-2-tunneling-protocol] Variable length, as specified by the offset size.
[src:vpn-tunneling/layer-2-tunneling-protocol] At the time of setup of L2TP connection, many control packets are exchanged between server and client to establish tunnel and session for each direction.
[src:vpn-tunneling/layer-2-tunneling-protocol] One peer requests the other peer to assign a specific tunnel and session id through these control packets.
[src:vpn-tunneling/layer-2-tunneling-protocol] Then using this tunnel and session id, data packets are exchanged with the compressed PPP frames as payload.
[src:vpn-tunneling/layer-2-tunneling-protocol] Because of the lack of confidentiality inherent in the L2TP, it is often implemented along with IPsec.
[src:vpn-tunneling/layer-2-tunneling-protocol] This is referred to as L2TP/IPsec, and is standardized in IETF RFC 3193.
[src:vpn-tunneling/layer-2-tunneling-protocol] Establishment of Encapsulating Security Payload (ESP) communication in transport mode.
[src:vpn-tunneling/layer-2-tunneling-protocol] The IP protocol number for ESP is 50 (compare TCP's 6 and UDP's 17).
[src:vpn-tunneling/layer-2-tunneling-protocol] At this point, a secure channel has been established, but no tunneling is taking place.
[src:vpn-tunneling/layer-2-tunneling-protocol] Negotiation and establishment of L2TP tunnel between the SA endpoints.
[src:vpn-tunneling/layer-2-tunneling-protocol] The actual negotiation of parameters takes place over the SA's secure channel, within the IPsec encryption.
[src:vpn-tunneling/layer-2-tunneling-protocol] When the process is complete, L2TP packets between the endpoints are encapsulated by IPsec.
[src:vpn-tunneling/layer-2-tunneling-protocol] Since the L2TP packet itself is wrapped and hidden within the IPsec packet, the original source and destination IP address is encrypted within the packet.
[src:vpn-tunneling/layer-2-tunneling-protocol] Also, it is not necessary to open UDP port 1701 on firewalls between the endpoints, since the inner packets are not acted upon until after IPsec data has been decrypted and stripped, which only takes place at the endpoints.
[src:vpn-tunneling/layer-2-tunneling-protocol] A potential point of confusion in L2TP/IPsec is the use of the terms **tunnel** and **secure channel**.
[src:vpn-tunneling/layer-2-tunneling-protocol] The term **tunnel-mode** refers to a channel which allows untouched packets of one network to be transported over another network.
[src:vpn-tunneling/layer-2-tunneling-protocol] In the case of L2TP/PPP, it allows L2TP/PPP packets to be transported over IP.
[src:vpn-tunneling/layer-2-tunneling-protocol] A **secure channel** refers to a connection within which the confidentiality of all data is guaranteed.
[src:vpn-tunneling/layer-2-tunneling-protocol] In L2TP/IPsec, first IPsec provides a secure channel, then L2TP provides a tunnel.
[src:vpn-tunneling/layer-2-tunneling-protocol] IPsec also specifies a tunnel protocol: this is not used when a L2TP tunnel is used.
[src:vpn-tunneling/layer-2-tunneling-protocol] Windows has had native support (configurable in control panel) for L2TP since Windows 2000.
[src:vpn-tunneling/layer-2-tunneling-protocol] Windows Vista added 2 alternative tools, an MMC snap-in called "Windows Firewall with Advanced Security" (WFwAS) and the "netsh advfirewall" command-line tool.
[src:vpn-tunneling/layer-2-tunneling-protocol] One limitation with both of the WFwAS and netsh commands is that servers must be specified by IP address.
[src:vpn-tunneling/layer-2-tunneling-protocol] Windows 10 added the "Add-VpnConnection" and "Set-VpnConnectionIPsecConfiguration" PowerShell commands.
[src:vpn-tunneling/layer-2-tunneling-protocol] L2TP is often used by ISPs when internet service over for example ADSL or cable is being *resold*.
[src:vpn-tunneling/layer-2-tunneling-protocol] From the end user, packets travel over a wholesale network service provider's network to a server called a Broadband Remote Access Server (BRAS), a protocol converter and router combined.
[src:vpn-tunneling/layer-2-tunneling-protocol] On legacy networks the path from end user customer premises' equipment to the BRAS may be over an ATM network.
[src:vpn-tunneling/layer-2-tunneling-protocol] From there on, over an IP network, an L2TP tunnel runs from the BRAS (acting as LAC) to an LNS which is an edge router at the boundary of the ultimate destination ISP's IP network.
[src:vpn-tunneling/openvpn] OpenVPN allows peers to authenticate each other using pre-shared secret keys, certificates or username/password.
[src:vpn-tunneling/openvpn] When used in a multiclient-server configuration, it allows the server to release an authentication certificate for every client, using signatures and certificate authority.
[src:vpn-tunneling/openvpn] It uses the OpenSSL encryption library extensively, as well as the TLS protocol, and contains many security and control features.
[src:vpn-tunneling/openvpn] As it uses a custom security protocol that utilizes SSL/TLS for key exchange.
[src:vpn-tunneling/openvpn] It is capable of traversing network address translators (NATs) and firewalls.
[src:vpn-tunneling/openvpn] OpenVPN has been ported and embedded on several systems.
[src:vpn-tunneling/openvpn] For example, DD-WRT has the OpenVPN server function.
[src:vpn-tunneling/openvpn] SoftEther VPN, a multi-protocol VPN server, also has an implementation of the OpenVPN protocol.
[src:vpn-tunneling/openvpn] It was written by James Yonan and is free software, released under the terms of the GNU General Public License version 2 (GPLv2).
[src:vpn-tunneling/openvpn] Additionally, commercial licenses are available.
[src:vpn-tunneling/openvpn] OpenVPN uses the OpenSSL library to provide encryption of both the data and control channels.
[src:vpn-tunneling/openvpn] It lets OpenSSL do all the encryption and authentication work, allowing OpenVPN to use all the ciphers available in the OpenSSL package.
[src:vpn-tunneling/openvpn] It can also use the HMAC packet authentication feature to add an additional layer of security to the connection (referred to as an "HMAC Firewall" by the creator).
[src:vpn-tunneling/openvpn] It can also use hardware acceleration to get better encryption performance.
[src:vpn-tunneling/openvpn] Support for mbed TLS is available starting from version 2.3.
[src:vpn-tunneling/openvpn] OpenVPN has several ways to authenticate peers with each other.
[src:vpn-tunneling/openvpn] OpenVPN offers pre-shared keys, certificate-based, and username/password-based authentication.
[src:vpn-tunneling/openvpn] Preshared secret key is the easiest, and certificate-based is the most robust and feature-rich.
[src:vpn-tunneling/openvpn] In version 2.0, username/password authentications can be enabled, both with or without certificates.
[src:vpn-tunneling/openvpn] However, to make use of username/password authentications, OpenVPN depends on third-party modules.
[src:vpn-tunneling/openvpn] OpenVPN can run over User Datagram Protocol (UDP) or Transmission Control Protocol (TCP) transports, multiplexing created SSL tunnels on a single TCP/UDP port (RFC 3948 for UDP).
[src:vpn-tunneling/openvpn] From 2.3.x series on, OpenVPN fully supports IPv6 as a protocol of the virtual network inside a tunnel and the OpenVPN applications can also establish connections via IPv6.
[src:vpn-tunneling/openvpn] It has the ability to work through most proxy servers (including HTTP) and is good at working through network address translation (NAT) and getting out through firewalls.
[src:vpn-tunneling/openvpn] The server configuration can "push" certain network configuration options to the clients.
[src:vpn-tunneling/openvpn] These include IP addresses, routing commands, and a few connection options.
[src:vpn-tunneling/openvpn] OpenVPN offers two types of interfaces for networking via the Universal TUN/TAP driver.
[src:vpn-tunneling/openvpn] It can create either a layer-3 based IP tunnel (TUN), or a layer-2 based Ethernet TAP that can carry any type of Ethernet traffic.
[src:vpn-tunneling/openvpn] OpenVPN can optionally use the LZO compression library to compress the data stream.
[src:vpn-tunneling/openvpn] Port 1194 is the official IANA assigned port number for OpenVPN.
[src:vpn-tunneling/openvpn] Newer versions of the program now default to that port.
[src:vpn-tunneling/openvpn] A feature in the 2.0 version allows for one process to manage several simultaneous tunnels, as opposed to the original "one tunnel per process" restriction on the 1.x series.
[src:vpn-tunneling/openvpn] OpenVPN's use of common network protocols (TCP and UDP) makes it a desirable alternative to IPsec in situations where an ISP may block specific VPN protocols in order to force users to subscribe to a higher-priced, "business grade" service tier.
[src:vpn-tunneling/openvpn] For example, Comcast previously declared that their @Home product was, and had always been, designated as a residential service and did not allow the use of commercial applications.
[src:vpn-tunneling/openvpn] Their argument was that conducting remote work via a VPN can adversely affect the network performance of their regular residential subscribers.
[src:vpn-tunneling/openvpn] They offered an alternative, @Home Professional, which would cost more than the @Home product.
[src:vpn-tunneling/openvpn] So, anyone wishing to use a VPN would have to subscribe to a higher-priced, business-grade service tier.
[src:vpn-tunneling/openvpn] When OpenVPN uses Transmission Control Protocol (TCP) transports to establish a tunnel, performance will be acceptable only as long as there is sufficient excess bandwidth on the un-tunneled network link to guarantee that the tunneled TCP timers do not expire.
[src:vpn-tunneling/openvpn] If this becomes untrue, performance falls off dramatically due to the TCP meltdown problem.
[src:vpn-tunneling/openvpn] OpenVPN offers various internal security features.
[src:vpn-tunneling/openvpn] It has up to 256-bit encryption through the OpenSSL library, although some service providers may offer lower rates, effectively providing some of the fastest VPN available to consumers.
[src:vpn-tunneling/openvpn] OpenVPN also supports Perfect Forward Secrecy (PFS), which regenerates encryption keys at set intervals, ensuring that even if one key is compromised, previous and future data remains secure.
[src:vpn-tunneling/openvpn] Additionally, OpenVPN can be configured with various encryption ciphers, such as ChaCha20 and AES-256.
[src:vpn-tunneling/openvpn] It runs in userspace instead of requiring IP stack (therefore kernel) operation.
[src:vpn-tunneling/openvpn] OpenVPN has the ability to drop root privileges, use mlockall to prevent swapping sensitive data to disk, enter a chroot jail after initialization, and apply a SELinux context after initialization.
[src:vpn-tunneling/openvpn] OpenVPN runs a custom security protocol based on SSL and TLS, rather than supporting IKE, IPsec, L2TP or PPTP.
[src:vpn-tunneling/openvpn] OpenVPN supports the use of smart cards via PKCS#11-based cryptographic tokens.
[src:vpn-tunneling/openvpn] OpenVPN can be extended with third-party plug-ins or scripts, which can be called at defined entry points.
[src:vpn-tunneling/openvpn] The purpose of this is often to extend OpenVPN with more advanced logging, enhanced authentication with username and passwords, dynamic firewall updates, RADIUS integration and so on.
[src:vpn-tunneling/openvpn] The plug-ins are dynamically loadable modules, usually written in C, while the scripts interface can execute any scripts or binaries available to OpenVPN.
[src:vpn-tunneling/openvpn] In the OpenVPN source code there are some examples of such plug-ins, including a PAM authentication plug-in.
[src:vpn-tunneling/openvpn] Several third-party plug-ins also exist to authenticate against LDAP or SQL databases such as SQLite and MySQL.
[src:vpn-tunneling/openvpn] This is an example for an OpenVPN control channel packet when HMAC based auth is enabled (tls-auth option in OpenVPN).
[src:vpn-tunneling/openvpn] Data channel packets, which carry IP traffic, have a different format.
[src:vpn-tunneling/openvpn] It is available on Solaris, Linux, OpenBSD, FreeBSD, NetBSD, QNX, macOS and Windows XP and later.
[src:vpn-tunneling/openvpn] OpenVPN is available for mobile operating systems including Maemo, Windows Mobile 6.5 and below, iOS 3GS+ devices, jailbroken iOS 3.1.2+ devices, Android 4.0+ devices, and Android devices that have had the Cyanogenmod aftermarket firmware flashed or have the correct kernel module installed.
[src:vpn-tunneling/openvpn] It is not compatible with some mobile phone OSes, including Palm OS.
[src:vpn-tunneling/openvpn] It is not a "web-based" VPN shown as a web page such as Citrix or Terminal Services Web access; the program is installed independently and configured by editing text files manually, rather than through a GUI-based wizard.
[src:vpn-tunneling/openvpn] OpenVPN is not compatible with VPN clients that use the IPsec over L2TP or PPTP protocols.
[src:vpn-tunneling/openvpn] The entire package consists of one binary for both client and server connections, an optional configuration file, and one or more key files depending on the authentication method used.
[src:vpn-tunneling/openvpn] OpenVPN has been integrated into several router firmware packages allowing users to run OpenVPN in client or server mode from their network routers.
[src:vpn-tunneling/openvpn] A router running OpenVPN in client mode, for example, allows any device on a network to access a VPN without needing the capability to install OpenVPN.
[src:vpn-tunneling/openvpn] OpenVPN has also been implemented in some manufacturer router firmware.
[src:vpn-tunneling/openvpn] OpenVPN has been integrated into SoftEther VPN, an open-source multi-protocol VPN server, to allow users to connect to the VPN server from existing OpenVPN clients.
[src:vpn-tunneling/openvpn] OpenVPN is also integrated into Vyos, an open-source routing operating system forked from the Vyatta software router.
[src:vpn-tunneling/openvpn] OpenVPN connections can be easily detected using deep packet inspection, based on known header data of the transmitted packets, regardless of the protocol or port used.
[src:vpn-tunneling/openvpn] While deep packet inspection does not allow determining the contents of the encrypted tunnel, it can be used to block the connection, identify communication participants, and log related data.
[src:vpn-tunneling/openvpn] This is particularly important when the use of VPN connections is prohibited in certain environments, for example, in countries where encrypted connections are banned, or under civil legislation when circumventing network blocks in corporate networks.
[src:vpn-tunneling/tunneling-protocol] In computer networks, a **tunneling protocol** is a communication protocol that allows for the movement of data from one network to another.
[src:vpn-tunneling/tunneling-protocol] They can, for example, allow private communications to be sent across a public network (such as the Internet), or for one network protocol to be carried over an incompatible network, through a process called encapsulation.
[src:vpn-tunneling/tunneling-protocol] Because tunneling involves repackaging the traffic data into a different form, perhaps with encryption as standard, it can hide the nature of the traffic that is run through a tunnel.
[src:vpn-tunneling/tunneling-protocol] Tunneling protocols work by using the data portion of a packet (the payload) to carry the packets that actually provide the service.
[src:vpn-tunneling/tunneling-protocol] Tunneling uses a layered protocol model such as those of the OSI or TCP/IP protocol suite, but usually violates the layering when using the payload to carry a service not normally provided by the network.
[src:vpn-tunneling/tunneling-protocol] Typically, the delivery protocol operates at an equal or higher level in the layered model than the payload protocol.
[src:vpn-tunneling/tunneling-protocol] A tunneling protocol may, for example, allow a foreign protocol to run over a network that does not support that particular protocol, such as running IPv6 over IPv4.
[src:vpn-tunneling/tunneling-protocol] Another important use is to provide services that are impractical or unsafe to be offered using only the underlying network services, such as providing a corporate network address to a remote user whose physical network address is not part of the corporate network.
[src:vpn-tunneling/tunneling-protocol] Users can also use tunneling to "sneak through" a firewall, using a protocol that the firewall would normally block, but "wrapped" inside a protocol that the firewall does not block, such as HTTP.
[src:vpn-tunneling/tunneling-protocol] If the firewall policy does not specifically exclude this kind of "wrapping", this trick can function to get around the intended firewall policy (or any set of interlocked firewall policies).
[src:vpn-tunneling/tunneling-protocol] Another HTTP-based tunneling method uses the HTTP CONNECT method/command.
[src:vpn-tunneling/tunneling-protocol] A client issues the HTTP CONNECT command to an HTTP proxy.
[src:vpn-tunneling/tunneling-protocol] The proxy then makes a TCP connection to a particular server:port, and relays data between that server:port and the client connection.
[src:vpn-tunneling/tunneling-protocol] Because this creates a security hole, CONNECT-capable HTTP proxies commonly restrict access to the CONNECT method.
[src:vpn-tunneling/tunneling-protocol] The proxy allows connections only to specific ports, such as 443 for HTTPS.
[src:vpn-tunneling/tunneling-protocol] Other tunneling methods able to bypass network firewalls make use of different protocols such as DNS, MQTT, and SMS.
[src:vpn-tunneling/tunneling-protocol] As an example of network layer over network layer, Generic Routing Encapsulation (GRE), a protocol running over IP (IP protocol number 47), often serves to carry IP packets, with RFC 1918 private addresses, over the Internet using delivery packets with public IP addresses.
[src:vpn-tunneling/tunneling-protocol] In this case, the delivery and payload protocols are the same, but the payload addresses are incompatible with those of the delivery network.
[src:vpn-tunneling/tunneling-protocol] It is also possible to establish a connection using the data link layer.
[src:vpn-tunneling/tunneling-protocol] The Layer 2 Tunneling Protocol (L2TP) allows the transmission of frames between two nodes.
[src:vpn-tunneling/tunneling-protocol] A tunnel is not encrypted by default: the TCP/IP protocol chosen determines the level of security.
[src:vpn-tunneling/tunneling-protocol] SSH uses port 22 to enable data encryption of payloads being transmitted over a public network (such as the Internet) connection, thereby providing VPN functionality.
[src:vpn-tunneling/tunneling-protocol] IPsec has an end-to-end Transport Mode, but can also operate in a tunneling mode through a trusted security gateway.
[src:vpn-tunneling/tunneling-protocol] To understand a particular protocol stack imposed by tunneling, network engineers must understand both the payload and delivery protocol sets.
[src:vpn-tunneling/tunneling-protocol] The throughput of a TCP‑over‑TCP connection can be degraded because the control loops in the inner and outer TCPs interfere destructively with each other.
[src:vpn-tunneling/tunneling-protocol] Because TCP is designed to guarantee in‑order and complete packet delivery, the outer TCP masks the connection's health from the inner TCP.
[src:vpn-tunneling/tunneling-protocol] In normal TCP operation, packet loss is detected when the receiver replies with duplicate ACKs to a packet received before the missing packet in the sequence.
[src:vpn-tunneling/tunneling-protocol] In response, the sender retransmits the lost packet and halves the Congestion Window (CWND).
[src:vpn-tunneling/tunneling-protocol] In TCP‑over‑TCP, the outer TCP handles lost packets normally through retransmission and CWND reduction.
[src:vpn-tunneling/tunneling-protocol] Still, since the inner TCP has not received any information indicating latency in the connection, it continues to transmit packets at the rate currently governed by its CWND.
[src:vpn-tunneling/tunneling-protocol] Because the inner TCP’s CWND is greater than the outer TCP’s, the outer TCP’s send buffer eventually fills.
[src:vpn-tunneling/tunneling-protocol] As the buffer inflates, packets experience longer and more variable queueing delays before transmission, thereby increasing the outer TCP’s measured round-trip time (RTT) and RTT variability.
[src:vpn-tunneling/tunneling-protocol] This inflates its retransmission timeout (RTO).
[src:vpn-tunneling/tunneling-protocol] Once the send buffer becomes full, the tunnel process can no longer forward inner‑TCP ACKs, so the inner TCP stops receiving acknowledgments entirely.
[src:vpn-tunneling/tunneling-protocol] Because the inner TCP is no longer receiving ACKs, its RTO expires, causing it to retransmit the oldest unacknowledged segment and double its RTO.
[src:vpn-tunneling/tunneling-protocol] The inner TCP’s RTO then grows exponentially because it doubles with every timeout, and no ACKs are received to reset it.
[src:vpn-tunneling/tunneling-protocol] The result of a TCP meltdown is an outer TCP with a severely reduced CWND, an inflated RTO, and a full send buffer.
[src:vpn-tunneling/tunneling-protocol] This indicates that the inner TCP cannot write and that ACKs are not being sent in either direction.
[src:vpn-tunneling/tunneling-protocol] A *Secure Shell (SSH) tunnel* consists of an encrypted tunnel created through an SSH protocol connection.
[src:vpn-tunneling/tunneling-protocol] Users may set up SSH tunnels to transfer unencrypted traffic over a network through an encrypted channel.
[src:vpn-tunneling/tunneling-protocol] It is a software-based approach to network security and the result is transparent encryption.
[src:vpn-tunneling/tunneling-protocol] For example, Microsoft Windows machines can share files using the Server Message Block (SMB) protocol, a non-encrypted protocol.
[src:vpn-tunneling/tunneling-protocol] If one were to mount a Microsoft Windows file-system remotely through the Internet, someone snooping on the connection could see transferred files.
[src:vpn-tunneling/tunneling-protocol] To mount the Windows file-system securely, one can establish a SSH tunnel that routes all SMB traffic to the remote fileserver through an encrypted channel.
[src:vpn-tunneling/tunneling-protocol] Even though the SMB protocol itself contains no encryption, the encrypted SSH channel through which it travels offers security.
[src:vpn-tunneling/tunneling-protocol] Once an SSH connection has been established, the tunnel starts with SSH listening to a port on the remote or local host.
[src:vpn-tunneling/tunneling-protocol] Any connections to it are forwarded to the specified address and port originating from the opposing (remote or local, as previously) host.
[src:vpn-tunneling/tunneling-protocol] Naturally, this wrapping and unwrapping also occurs in the reverse direction of the bidirectional tunnel.
[src:vpn-tunneling/tunneling-protocol] SSH tunnels provide a means to bypass firewalls that prohibit certain Internet services – so long as a site allows outgoing connections.
[src:vpn-tunneling/tunneling-protocol] For example, an organization may prohibit a user from accessing Internet web pages (port 80) directly without passing through the organization's proxy filter (which provides the organization with a means of monitoring and controlling what the user sees through the web).
[src:vpn-tunneling/tunneling-protocol] But users may not wish to have their web traffic monitored or blocked by the organisation's proxy filter.
[src:vpn-tunneling/tunneling-protocol] If users can connect to an external SSH server, they can create an SSH tunnel to forward a given port on their local machine to port 80 on a remote web server.
[src:vpn-tunneling/tunneling-protocol] Some SSH clients support dynamic port forwarding that allows the user to create a SOCKS 4/5 proxy.
[src:vpn-tunneling/tunneling-protocol] In this case users can configure their applications to use their local SOCKS proxy server.
[src:vpn-tunneling/tunneling-protocol] This gives more flexibility than creating an SSH tunnel to a single port as previously described.
[src:vpn-tunneling/tunneling-protocol] SOCKS can free the user from the limitations of connecting only to a predefined remote port and server.
[src:vpn-tunneling/tunneling-protocol] If an application does not support SOCKS, a proxifier can be used to redirect the application to the local SOCKS proxy server.
[src:vpn-tunneling/tunneling-protocol] Some proxifiers, such as Proxycap, support SSH directly, thus avoiding the need for an SSH client.
[src:vpn-tunneling/tunneling-protocol] In recent versions of OpenSSH it is even allowed to create layer 2 or layer 3 tunnels if both ends have enabled such tunneling capabilities.
[src:vpn-tunneling/tunneling-protocol] This creates `tun` (layer 3, default) or `tap` (layer 2) virtual interfaces on both ends of the connection.
[src:vpn-tunneling/tunneling-protocol] This allows normal network management and routing to be used, and when used on routers, the traffic for an entire subnetwork can be tunneled.
[src:vpn-tunneling/tunneling-protocol] A pair of `tap` virtual interfaces function like an Ethernet cable connecting both ends of the connection and can join kernel bridges.
[src:vpn-tunneling/tunneling-protocol] Over the years, tunneling and data encapsulation have in very rare cases been adopted for malicious reasons, in order to maliciously communicate outside of a protected network.
[src:vpn-tunneling/tunneling-protocol] In this context, known tunnels involve protocols such as HTTP, SSH, DNS, MQTT.
[src:vpn-tunneling/virtual-private-network] A **virtual private network** (**VPN**) is an overlay network that uses network virtualization to extend a private network across a public network, such as the Internet, via the use of encryption and tunneling protocols.
[src:vpn-tunneling/virtual-private-network] In a VPN, a tunneling protocol is used to transfer network messages from one network host to another.
[src:vpn-tunneling/virtual-private-network] Host-to-network VPNs are commonly used by organizations to allow off-site users secure access to an office network over the Internet.
[src:vpn-tunneling/virtual-private-network] Site-to-site VPNs connect two networks, such as an office network and a datacenter.
[src:vpn-tunneling/virtual-private-network] Provider-provisioned VPNs isolate parts of the provider's own network infrastructure in virtual segments, in ways that make the contents of each segment private with respect to the others.
[src:vpn-tunneling/virtual-private-network] Individuals also use VPNs to encrypt and attempt to anonymize their network traffic, with VPN services selling access to their own private networks.
[src:vpn-tunneling/virtual-private-network] VPNs can enhance usage privacy by making an ISP unable to access the private data exchanged across the VPN.
[src:vpn-tunneling/virtual-private-network] However, the VPN provider and the online service being accessed via the VPN may have visibility of the user's activities.
[src:vpn-tunneling/virtual-private-network] Through encryption, VPNs enhance confidentiality and reduce the risk of successful external data sniffing attacks.
[src:vpn-tunneling/virtual-private-network] A network is a group of communicating computers known as hosts, which communicate data to other hosts via communication protocols, as facilitated by networking hardware.
[src:vpn-tunneling/virtual-private-network] Within a computer network, computers are identified by network addresses, which allow rule-based systems such as Internet Protocol (IP) to locate and identify hosts.
[src:vpn-tunneling/virtual-private-network] Hosts may also have hostnames, memorable labels for the host nodes, which are rarely changed after initial assignment.
[src:vpn-tunneling/virtual-private-network] The transmission medium that supports information exchange includes wired media like copper cables, optical fibers, and wireless radio-frequency media.
[src:vpn-tunneling/virtual-private-network] The arrangement of hosts and hardware within a network architecture is known as the network topology.
[src:vpn-tunneling/virtual-private-network] A communication protocol is a set of rules for exchanging information over a network.
[src:vpn-tunneling/virtual-private-network] Communication protocols have various characteristics, such as being connection-oriented or connectionless, or using circuit switching or packet switching.
[src:vpn-tunneling/virtual-private-network] In a protocol stack, often constructed per the OSI model, communications functions are divided into protocol layers, where each layer leverages the services of the layer below it until the lowest layer controls the hardware that sends information across the media.
[src:vpn-tunneling/virtual-private-network] The use of protocol layering is ubiquitous across the field of computer networking.
[src:vpn-tunneling/virtual-private-network] An important example of a protocol stack is HTTP, the World Wide Web protocol.
[src:vpn-tunneling/virtual-private-network] HTTP runs over TCP over IP, the internet protocols, which in turn run over IEEE 802.11, the Wi-Fi protocol.
[src:vpn-tunneling/virtual-private-network] This stack is used between a wireless router and a personal computer when accessing the web.
[src:vpn-tunneling/virtual-private-network] Most modern computer networks use protocols based on packet-mode transmission.
[src:vpn-tunneling/virtual-private-network] A network packet is a formatted unit of data carried by a packet-switched network.
[src:vpn-tunneling/virtual-private-network] Packets consist of two types of data: control information and user data (payload).
[src:vpn-tunneling/virtual-private-network] The control information provides data the network needs to deliver the user data, for example, source and destination network addresses, error detection codes, and sequencing information.
[src:vpn-tunneling/virtual-private-network] Typically, control information is found in packet headers and trailers, with payload data in between.
[src:vpn-tunneling/virtual-private-network] The Internet protocol suite, also called TCP/IP, is the foundation of all modern networking and the defining set of protocols for the Internet.
[src:vpn-tunneling/virtual-private-network] It offers connection-less and connection-oriented services over an inherently unreliable network traversed by datagram transmission using Internet protocol (IP).
[src:vpn-tunneling/virtual-private-network] At its core, the protocol suite defines the addressing, identification, and routing specifications for Internet Protocol Version 4 (IPv4) and for IPv6, the next generation of the protocol with a much enlarged addressing capability.
[src:vpn-tunneling/virtual-private-network] VPNs do not make connected users anonymous or unidentifiable to the untrusted medium network provider, such as an Internet service provider (ISP).
[src:vpn-tunneling/virtual-private-network] However, VPNs can enhance usage privacy by making an ISP unable to access the private data exchanged across the VPN.
[src:vpn-tunneling/virtual-private-network] Through encryption, VPNs enhance confidentiality and reduce the risk of successful data sniffing attacks.
[src:vpn-tunneling/virtual-private-network] Data packets travelling across a VPN may also be secured by tamper proofing via a message authentication code, prevents the message from being altered or tampered without being rejected, enhancing data integrity.
[src:vpn-tunneling/virtual-private-network] A number of other implementations exist to ensure authentication of connecting parties.
[src:vpn-tunneling/virtual-private-network] Tunnel endpoints can be authenticated in various ways during the VPN access initiation, such as by the whitelisting of endpoint IP address.
[src:vpn-tunneling/virtual-private-network] Authentication may also occur after actual tunnels are already active, for example, with a web captive portal.
[src:vpn-tunneling/virtual-private-network] Remote-access VPNs may also use passwords, biometrics, two-factor authentication, or other cryptographic methods.
[src:vpn-tunneling/virtual-private-network] Site-to-site VPNs often use passwords (pre-shared keys) or digital certificates.
[src:vpn-tunneling/virtual-private-network] Split tunneling allows a user to access distinct security domains at the same time, using the same or different network connections.
[src:vpn-tunneling/virtual-private-network] This connection state is usually facilitated through the simultaneous use of a LAN network interface controller (NIC), radio NIC, Wireless LAN NIC, and virtual private network client software application.
[src:vpn-tunneling/virtual-private-network] Split tunneling is most commonly configured via the use of a remote-access VPN client, which allows the user to simultaneously connect to a nearby wireless network, resources on an off-site corporate network, as well as websites over the Internet.
[src:vpn-tunneling/virtual-private-network] Advantages of split tunneling include alleviating bottlenecks, conserving bandwidth (as Internet traffic does not have to pass through the VPN server), and enabling a user to not have to continually connect and disconnect when remotely accessing resources..
[src:vpn-tunneling/virtual-private-network] Disadvantages include DNS leaks and potentially bypassing gateway-level security that might be in place within the company infrastructure.
[src:vpn-tunneling/virtual-private-network] Internet service providers often use split tunneling to that implement for DNS hijacking purposes.
[src:vpn-tunneling/virtual-private-network] A *host-to-network* configuration is analogous to joining one or more computers to a network to which they cannot be directly connected.
[src:vpn-tunneling/virtual-private-network] This type of extension provides computer access to a local area network of a remote site, or any wider enterprise networks, such as an intranet.
[src:vpn-tunneling/virtual-private-network] Each computer is in charge of activating its own tunnel towards the network it wants to join.
[src:vpn-tunneling/virtual-private-network] The joined network is only aware of a single remote host for each tunnel.
[src:vpn-tunneling/virtual-private-network] This may be employed for remote workers, or to enable people accessing their private home or company resources without exposing them on the public Internet.
[src:vpn-tunneling/virtual-private-network] A *site-to-site* configuration connects two networks.
[src:vpn-tunneling/virtual-private-network] This configuration expands a network across geographically disparate locations.
[src:vpn-tunneling/virtual-private-network] Tunneling is only done between gateway devices located at each network location.
[src:vpn-tunneling/virtual-private-network] These devices then make the tunnel available to other local network hosts that aim to reach any host on the other side.
[src:vpn-tunneling/virtual-private-network] This is useful to keep sites connected to each other in a stable manner, like office networks to their headquarters or datacenter.
[src:vpn-tunneling/virtual-private-network] In this case, any side may be configured to initiate the communication as long as it knows how to reach the other.
[src:vpn-tunneling/virtual-private-network] In the context of site-to-site configurations, the terms *intranet* and *extranet* are used to describe two different use cases.
[src:vpn-tunneling/virtual-private-network] An *intranet* site-to-site VPN describes a configuration where the sites connected by the VPN belong to the same organization, whereas an *extranet* site-to-site VPN joins sites belonging to multiple organizations.
[src:vpn-tunneling/virtual-private-network] A limitation of traditional VPNs is that they are point-to-point connections and do not tend to support broadcast domains.
[src:vpn-tunneling/virtual-private-network] Therefore, communication, software, and networking that are based on layer 2 and broadcast packets (such as NetBIOS used in Windows networking) may not be fully supported as on a local area network.
[src:vpn-tunneling/virtual-private-network] Variants on VPN such as Virtual Private LAN Service (VPLS) and layer 2 tunneling protocols are designed to overcome this limitation.
[src:vpn-tunneling/virtual-private-network] Trusted VPNs do not use cryptographic tunneling; instead, they rely on the security of a single provider's network to protect the traffic.
[src:vpn-tunneling/virtual-private-network] Multiprotocol Label Switching (MPLS) often overlays trusted VPNs, often with quality-of-service control over a trusted delivery network.
[src:vpn-tunneling/virtual-private-network] A secure VPN either trusts the underlying delivery network or enforces security with an internal mechanism.
[src:vpn-tunneling/virtual-private-network] Unless the trusted delivery network runs among physically secure sites only, both trusted and secure models need an authentication mechanism for users to gain access to the VPN.
[src:vpn-tunneling/virtual-private-network] Mobile VPNs are widely used in public safety where they give law-enforcement officers access to applications such as computer-assisted dispatch and criminal databases, and in other organizations with similar requirements such as field service management and healthcare.
[src:vpn-tunneling/virtual-private-network] Dynamic Multipoint Virtual Private Network (DMVPN) is a dynamic tunneling form of a virtual private network supported on Cisco IOS-based routers, Huawei AR G3 routers, and Unix-like operating systems.
[src:vpn-tunneling/virtual-private-network] DMVPN provides the capability for creating a dynamic-mesh VPN network without having to statically pre-configure all possible tunnel end-point peers, such as IPsec and ISAKMP peers.
[src:vpn-tunneling/virtual-private-network] DMVPN is initially configured to build a hub-and-spoke network by statically configuring the hubs (VPN headends) on the spokes; no change in the configuration on the hub is required to accept new spokes.
[src:vpn-tunneling/virtual-private-network] Using this initial hub-and-spoke network, tunnels between spokes are dynamically built on demand without additional configuration on the hubs or spokes.
[src:vpn-tunneling/virtual-private-network] This dynamic-mesh capability alleviates the need for any load on the hub to route data between the spoke networks.
[src:vpn-tunneling/virtual-private-network] Ethernet VPN (EVPN) is a technology for carrying OSI layer 2 Ethernet traffic as a virtual private network using wide area network protocols.
[src:vpn-tunneling/virtual-private-network] Multiprotocol Label Switching (MPLS) is a routing technique in telecommunications networks that directs data from one node to the next based on labels rather than network addresses.
[src:vpn-tunneling/virtual-private-network] Whereas network addresses identify endpoints, MPLS labels identify established paths between endpoints.
[src:vpn-tunneling/virtual-private-network] MPLS can encapsulate packets of various network protocols.
[src:vpn-tunneling/virtual-private-network] In practice, MPLS is mainly used to forward IP protocol data units and Virtual Private LAN Service Ethernet traffic.
[src:vpn-tunneling/virtual-private-network] Major applications of MPLS are telecommunications traffic engineering and MPLS VPN.
[src:vpn-tunneling/virtual-private-network] Virtual Private LAN Service (VPLS) is a virtual private network technology that provides Ethernet-based multipoint-to-multipoint communication over IP or MPLS networks.
[src:vpn-tunneling/virtual-private-network] It allows geographically dispersed sites to share an Ethernet broadcast domain by connecting sites (including both servers and clients) through pseudowires.
[src:vpn-tunneling/virtual-private-network] The technologies that can be used as pseudo-wire can be Ethernet over MPLS, L2TPv3 or even GRE.
[src:vpn-tunneling/virtual-private-network] There are two IETF standards-track RFCs (RFC 4761 and RFC 4762) describing VPLS establishment.
[src:vpn-tunneling/virtual-private-network] In contrast to L2TPv3, which allows only point-to-point OSI layer 2 tunnels, VPLS allows any-to-any (multipoint) connectivity.
[src:vpn-tunneling/virtual-private-network] A virtual private network is based on a tunneling protocol, and may be combined with other network or application protocols to provide additional security and capabilities.
[src:vpn-tunneling/virtual-private-network] Internet Protocol Security (IPsec) is a standards-based security protocol, initially developed by the Internet Engineering Task Force (IETF) for IPv6, and was required in all standards-compliant implementations of IPv6 before RFC 6434 made it only a recommendation.
[src:vpn-tunneling/virtual-private-network] The design of IPSec meets most security goals: availability, integrity, and confidentiality.
[src:vpn-tunneling/virtual-private-network] IPsec uses encryption, encapsulating an IP packet inside an IPsec packet.
[src:vpn-tunneling/virtual-private-network] De-encapsulation happens at the end of the tunnel, where the original IP packet is decrypted and forwarded to its intended destination.
[src:vpn-tunneling/virtual-private-network] IPsec is also often supported by network hardware accelerators, which makes IPsec VPN desirable for low-power scenarios, like always-on remote access VPN configurations.
[src:vpn-tunneling/virtual-private-network] IPsec tunnels are set up by the Internet Key Exchange (IKE) protocol.
[src:vpn-tunneling/virtual-private-network] IPsec tunnels made with IKE version 1 (also known as IKEv1 tunnels, or often just "IPsec tunnels") can be used alone to provide VPN but are often combined with the Layer 2 Tunneling Protocol (L2TP) to reuse existing L2TP-related implementations for more flexible authentication features (e.g.
[src:vpn-tunneling/virtual-private-network] IKE version 2, which was created by Microsoft and Cisco, can be used alone to provide IPsec VPN functionality.
[src:vpn-tunneling/virtual-private-network] Its primary advantages are the native support for authenticating via the Extensible Authentication Protocol (EAP) and that the tunnel can be seamlessly restored when the IP address of the associated host is changing, which is typical of a roaming mobile device, whether on 3G or 4G LTE networks.
[src:vpn-tunneling/virtual-private-network] Transport Layer Security (SSL/TLS) can tunnel an entire network's traffic (as it does in the OpenVPN project and SoftEther VPN project) or secure an individual connection.
[src:vpn-tunneling/virtual-private-network] A number of vendors provide remote-access VPN capabilities through TLS.
[src:vpn-tunneling/virtual-private-network] A VPN based on TLS can connect from locations where the usual TLS web navigation (HTTPS) is supported without requiring additional configuration.
[src:vpn-tunneling/virtual-private-network] OpenSSH offers VPN tunneling (distinct from port forwarding) to secure remote connections to a network, inter-network links, and remote systems.
[src:vpn-tunneling/virtual-private-network] OpenSSH server provides a limited number of concurrent tunnels.
[src:vpn-tunneling/virtual-private-network] The VPN feature itself does not support personal authentication.
[src:vpn-tunneling/virtual-private-network] SSH is more often used to remotely connect to machines or networks instead of a site to site VPN connection.
[src:vpn-tunneling/virtual-private-network] OpenVPN is a free and open-source VPN protocol based on the TLS protocol.
[src:vpn-tunneling/virtual-private-network] It supports perfect forward-secrecy, and most modern secure cipher suites, like AES, Serpent, TwoFish, etc.
[src:vpn-tunneling/virtual-private-network] It is currently being developed and updated by OpenVPN Inc., a non-profit providing secure VPN technologies.
[src:vpn-tunneling/virtual-private-network] Secure Socket Tunneling Protocol (SSTP) is a form of VPN tunnel that provides a mechanism to transport Point-to-Point Protocol (PPP) traffic through an SSL/TLS channel.
[src:vpn-tunneling/virtual-private-network] WireGuard is a protocol designed to be more lightweight than OpenVPN.
[src:vpn-tunneling/virtual-private-network] In 2020, WireGuard support was added to both the Linux and Android kernels, opening it up to adoption by VPN providers.
[src:vpn-tunneling/virtual-private-network] By default, WireGuard utilizes the Curve25519 protocol for key exchange and ChaCha20-Poly1305 for encryption and message authentication, but also includes the ability to pre-share a symmetric key between the client and server.
[src:vpn-tunneling/virtual-private-network] Desktop, smartphone and other end-user device operating systems usually support configuring remote access VPN from their graphical or command-line tools.
[src:vpn-tunneling/virtual-private-network] However, due to the variety of, often non standard, VPN protocols, there exist many third-party applications that implement additional protocols not yet or no longer natively supported by the OS.
[src:vpn-tunneling/virtual-private-network] For instance, Android lacked native IPsec IKEv2 support until version 11, and users needed to install third-party apps in order to connect that kind of VPN.
[src:vpn-tunneling/virtual-private-network] Conversely, Windows does not natively support plain IPsec IKEv1 remote access native VPN configuration (commonly used by Cisco and Fritz!Box VPN solutions).
[src:vpn-tunneling/virtual-private-network] Network appliances, such as firewalls, often include VPN gateway functionality for either remote access or site-to-site configurations.
[src:vpn-tunneling/virtual-private-network] Their administration interfaces often facilitate setting up virtual private networks with a selection of supported protocols.
[src:vpn-tunneling/virtual-private-network] In some cases, like in the open source operating systems devoted to firewalls and network devices (like OpenWrt, IPFire, PfSense or OPNsense), it is possible to add support for additional VPN protocols by installing missing software components or third-party apps.
[src:vpn-tunneling/virtual-private-network] Commercial appliances with VPN features based on proprietary hardware or software platforms usually support a consistent VPN protocol across their products, but do not allow customizations outside the use cases they implement.
[src:vpn-tunneling/virtual-private-network] This is often the case for appliances that rely on hardware acceleration of VPNs to provide higher throughput or support a larger number of simultaneously connected users.
[src:vpn-tunneling/virtual-private-network] According to a 2022 estimate, 3% of Chinese netizens use VPNs, compared to 8.5% of Americans.
[src:vpn-tunneling/virtual-private-network] In China, VPNs are increasingly blocked and unauthorized usage can be subject to fines and legal prosecution.
[src:vpn-tunneling/virtual-private-network] Based on its estimates of leaked government documents, ChinaFile estimated in 2026 that VPN demand in China was in the low single digits.
[src:vpn-tunneling/virtual-private-network] It also estimated that foreign apps blocked by the Great Firewall have extremely low traffic, particularly compared to domestic apps; the top five domestic apps saw traffic that was 1,000 times more than the top five foreign apps.
[src:vpn-tunneling/virtual-private-network] As of 2025, approximately 1.75 billion people used VPNs.
[src:vpn-tunneling/virtual-private-network] By 2027, this market is projected to grow to $76 billion.
[src:vpn-tunneling/virtual-private-network] Amid Internet restrictions and blocking in Russia, Internet activists created the Amnezia VPN project in 2020 during a digital rights hackathon organized by Roskomsvoboda.
[src:vpn-tunneling/virtual-private-network] The service gained popularity among Russian users by providing access to blocked resources, as well as features aimed at enhancing anonymity and resistance to traffic analysis.
